ue.svg|10px]]\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|{{flagicon|GBR}} [[Lewis Hamilton]]\n|align=\"left\"|345\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[File:1rightarrow blue.svg|10px]]\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|{{flagicon|GER}} [[Sebastian Vettel]]\n|align=\"left\"|302\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[File:1rightarrow blue.svg|10px]]\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|{{flagicon|FIN}} [[Valtteri Bottas]]\n|align=\"left\"|280\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[File:1rightarrow blue.svg|10px]]\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Daniel Ricciardo]]\n|align=\"left\"|200\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[File:1rightarrow blue.svg|10px]]\n|align=\"center\"|5\n|{{flagicon|FIN}} [[Kimi R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen]]\n|align=\"left\"|193\n|-\n!colspan=4|Source:<ref name=\"champ\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.statsf1.com/en/2017/bresil/championnat.aspx|title=Brazil 2017 - Championship \u2022 STATS F1|website=www.statsf1.com|access-date=13 March 2019}}</ref>\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n;Constructors' Championship standings\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 85%;\"\n|-\n!\n!{{Tooltip|Pos.|Position}}\n!Constructor\n!Points\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[File:1rightarrow blue.svg|10px]]\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|{{flagicon|GER}} [[Mercedes-Benz in Formula One|Mercedes]]\n|align=\"left\"|625\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[File:1rightarrow blue.svg|10px]]\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|{{flagicon|ITA}} [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n|align=\"left\"|495\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[File:1rightarrow blue.svg|10px]]\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|{{flagicon|AUT}} {{nowrap|[[Red Bull Racing]]-[[TAG Heuer]]}}\n|align=\"left\"|358\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[File:1rightarrow blue.svg|10px]]\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|{{flagicon|IND}} [[Force India]]-[[Mercedes AMG High Performance Powertrains|Mercedes]] \n|align=\"left\"|177\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[File:1rightarrow blue.svg|10px]]\n|align=\"center\"|5\n|{{flagicon|GBR}} [[Williams Grand Prix Engineering|Williams]]-[[Mercedes AMG High Performance Powertrains|Mercedes]]\n|align=\"left\"|82\n|-\n!colspan=4|Source:<ref name=\"champ\"/>\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{F1 race report\n| Name_of_race = [[Brazilian Grand Prix]]\n| Year_of_race = 2017\n| Previous_race_in_season = [[2017 Mexican Grand Prix]]\n| Next_race_in_season = [[2017 Abu Dhabi Grand Prix]]\n| Previous_year's_race = [[2016 Brazilian Grand Prix]]\n| Next_year's_race = [[2018 Brazilian Grand Prix]]\n}}\n\n{{F1GP 10-19}}\n\n[[Category:2017 Formula One races|Brazilian]]\n[[Category:Brazilian Grand Prix]]\n[[Category:2017 in Brazilian motorsport]]\n[[Category:November 2017 sports events in South America|Brazilian Grand Prix]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Infobox Grand Prix race report\n| Type           = F1\n| Country        = Brazil\n| Grand Prix     = Brazilian\n| Details ref    =<ref name=\"formal\">{{cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/championship/races/2017/Brazil.html|title=Brazil|work=formula1.com|accessdate=19 September 2017}}</ref>\n| Fulldate       = {{Start date|2017|11|12|df=y}}\n| Year           = 2017\n| Race_No        = 19\n| Season_No      = 20\n| Image          = File:2014 Interlagos circuit map.svg\n| Image_Link     = \n| image-size     = 200px\n| Official name  = Formula 1 Grande Pr\u00eamio [[Heineken]] do Brasil 2017<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.progcovers.com/motor/f12017.html|title=2017 Formula 1 World Championship Programmes - The Motor Racing Programme Covers Project|first=Malcolm|last=Mitchell|website=www.progcovers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.progcovers.com/motor/interlagos.html|title=Interlagos - The Motor Racing Programme Covers Project|first=Malcolm|last=Mitchell|website=www.progcovers.com}}</ref>\n| Caption = Layout of the Aut\u00f3dromo Jos\u00e9 Carlos Pace\n| Location       = [[Aut\u00f3dromo Jos\u00e9 Carlos Pace]], [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], [[Brazil]]\n| Course         = Permanent racing facility\n| Course_km      = 4.309\n| Course_mi      = 2.677\n| Distance_laps  = 71\n| Distance_km    = 305.909\n| Distance_mi    = 190.083\n| Pole_Driver    = [[Valtteri Bottas]]\n| Pole_Country   = FIN\n| Pole_Team      = [[Mercedes-Benz in Formula One|Mercedes]]\n| Pole_Time      = 1:08.322\n| Fast_Driver    = {{nowrap|{{flagicon|NED}} [[Max Verstappen]]}}\n| Fast_Team      = {{nowrap|[[Red Bull Racing]]-[[TAG Heuer]]}}\n| Fast_Time      = 1:11.044\n| Fast_Lap       = 64 \n| First_Driver   = {{nowrap|{{flagicon|GER}} [[Sebastian Vettel]]}}\n| First_Team     = [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n| Second_Driver  = [[Valtteri Bottas]]\n| Second_Country = FIN\n| Second_Team    = [[Mercedes-Benz in Formula One|Mercedes]]\n| Third_Driver   = [[Kimi R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen]]\n| Third_Country  = FIN\n| Third_Team     = [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n| Lapchart       = {{F1Laps2017|BRA}}\n| Attendance     = 141,218<ref>{{cite news|title=F1 reveals overall rise in 2017 attendance|url=https://www.gpupdate.net/en/f1-news/361717/f1-reveals-eight-per-cent-rise-in-2017-attendance/|work=[[GPupdate.net]]|publisher=[[JHED Media BV]]|date=8 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171209011037/https://www.gpupdate.net/en/f1-news/361717/f1-reveals-eight-per-cent-rise-in-2017-attendance/|archive-date=9 December 2017}}</ref>}}\n\nThe '''2017 Brazilian Grand Prix''' (formally known as the '''Formula 1 Grande Pr\u00eamio Heineken do Brasil 2017''') was a [[Formula One]] motor race held on 12 November 2017 at the [[Aut\u00f3dromo Jos\u00e9 Carlos Pace]] in the [[Interlagos]] neighborhood of [[S\u00e3o Paulo]], [[Brazil]]. The race was the nineteenth and penultimate round of the [[2017 FIA Formula One World Championship]] and marked the forty-sixth running of the [[Brazilian Grand Prix]], the forty-fifth time that the race had been run as a World Championship event since the inaugural season in {{F1|1950}}, and the thirty-fourth World Championship event to be held at Interlagos.\n\nMercedes driver [[Valtteri Bottas]] started from pole position with Ferrari's [[Sebastian Vettel]] and [[Kimi R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen]] behind, after World Champion [[Lewis Hamilton]] crashed out of qualifying early and started from the pit lane. Vettel overtook Bottas on the first corner, after which he set the pace through most of the race. Vettel won the Grand Prix, followed by Bottas and R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen. Hamilton eventually climbed to fourth, closing to less than one second of a podium finish.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/nov/12/sebastian-vettel-f1-brazilian-grand-prix-lewis-hamilton-race-report|title=Sebastian Vettel wins Brazilian Grand Prix after Lewis Hamilton fightback|date=13 November 2017|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Report==\n\n===Free practice===\nThe three free practice session demonstrated very tight competition between [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]] and [[Mercedes-Benz in Formula One|Mercedes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/headlines/2017/11/fp3---mercedes-and-ferrari-all-but-inseparable-at-interlagos.html|work=formula1.com|title=FP3 \u2013 Mercedes and Ferrari all but inseparable at Interlagos|accessdate=15 November 2017}}</ref> In first and second free practice, [[Lewis Hamilton]] was quickest, with both Ferraris and both [[Red Bull Racing|Red Bulls]] within one second. [[Felipe Massa]] and [[Fernando Alonso]] were notably strong in these sessions. In the third session, the order was similar. However, [[Valtteri Bottas]] pipped Hamilton's best time by three thousands of a second; and neither [[Max Verstappen]] nor Massa put in a strong lap. In the final practice round, less than a tenth of a second separated the two Mercedes and two Ferraris.\n\nThe first practice session saw [[George Russell (racing driver)|George Russell]]'s Formula One debut appearance. There was also an unusual appearance of a test driver ([[Antonio Giovinazzi]]) in the second practice session (usually, any test drivers that participate in a racing weekend, do so in the first practice session).\n\n===Qualifying===\nQualifying began in a dramatic fashion as World Champion Hamilton lost the back end of the car with over-steer, seemingly due to a driver error, crashing to retire from Q1 without setting a lap time. R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen was fastest in Q1 and Vettel in Q2. In the final qualifying session, however, Bottas took pole position. Vettel qualified a close second, followed by R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen, Verstappen and [[Daniel Ricciardo]]. Ricciardo took a 10-place grid penalty for exceeding his quota of power unit components and started 14th on the grid. Hamilton elected to change his gearbox and power unit, so started the race from the pit lane.\n\n===Race===\nVettel achieved a good start during the second phase of clutch control to overtake Bottas on the first corner. There were numerous retirements due to collisions on the first lap. [[Romain Grosjean]] lost the back end, clipping [[Esteban Ocon]] off the track. Ocon's resultant retirement ended his record streak of [[List of Formula One driver records#Other driver records|27 races finished]] from his Formula One debut. [[Stoffel Vandoorne]] and [[Kevin Magnussen]] also retired due to a collision on the first lap.\n\nHamilton, starting from the pit lane, implemented an inverted tyre strategy running to lap 44 on one set of soft tyres. After overtaking the back-markers and mid-field, he fell into first place as the leading cars \u2013 predominantly on one-stop strategies \u2013 pitted. Hamilton's only pit-stop positioned him fifth, after which he overtook Verstappen and was briefly able to challenge R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen for the podium,<ref name=\"auto\"/> but unable to overtake Raikkonen in third. Ricciardo also battled up to sixth after starting fifteenth on the grid and dropping to seventeenth as collateral of the Vandoorne-Magnussen collision.\n\nSetting the pace through most of the race, Vettel won the Grand Prix, followed by Bottas and R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen. Including Hamilton, the top four finished within the space of 5.5 seconds, with the two Red Bulls more than 30 seconds behind. The following three positions also carried a race-long battle to the finish line, finishing within 1 second of each other. Initially overtaking on lap 5 (as the safety car was pulling into pitlane), Massa held off Alonso who remained close throughout the race.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fia.com/file/63359/download?token=T3mowbXa |title=2017 Brazilian Grand Prix \u2013 Race History Chart |date=12 November 2017 |publisher=[[FIA]] |accessdate=18 November 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171118173350/https://www.fia.com/file/63359/download?token=T3mowbXa |archive-date=18 November 2017}}</ref> [[Sergio P\u00e9rez]] also caught up to these two racers to cross the finish line barely behind Alonso.\n\n==Classification==\n===Qualifying===\n{|class=wikitable style=\"font-size:85%\"\n!rowspan=2|{{Tooltip|Pos.|Qualifying position}}\n!rowspan=2|{{Tooltip|Car<br>no.|Number}}\n!rowspan=2|Driver\n!rowspan=2|Constructor\n!colspan=3| {{nowrap|Qualifying times}}\n!rowspan=2|{{Tooltip|Final<br>grid|Final grid position}}\n|-\n!Q1\n!Q2\n!Q3\n|-\n!1\n|align=\"center\"|77\n|{{flagicon|FIN}} [[Valtteri Bottas]] \n|[[Mercedes-Benz in Formula One|Mercedes]]\n|1:09.452\n|1:08.638\n|'''1:08.322'''\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n!2\n|align=\"center\"|5\n|{{flagicon|GER}} [[Sebastian Vettel]] \n|[[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n|1:09.643\n|'''1:08.494'''\n|1:08.360\n|align=\"center\"|2\n|-\n!3\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|{{flagicon|FIN}} [[Kimi R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen]]\n|[[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]\n|'''1:09.405'''\n|1:09.116\n|1:08.538\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n!4\n|align=\"center\"|33\n|{{flagicon|NED}} [[Max Verstappen]] \n|{{nowrap|[[Red Bull Racing]]-[[TAG Heuer]]}}\n|1:09.820\n|1:09.050\n|1:08.925\n|align=\"center\"|4\n|-\n!5\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|{{flagicon|AUS}} [[Daniel Ricciardo]] \n|{{nowrap|[[Red Bull Racing]]-[[TAG Heuer]]}}\n|1:09.828\n|1:09.533\n|1:09.330\n|align=\"center\"|14{{ref|1|1}}\n|-\n!6\n|align=\"center\"|11\n|{{flagicon|MEX}} [[Sergio P\u00e9rez]] \n|[[Force India]