{"title_page": "Sports in Aruba", "text_new": "{{copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n[[Aruba]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aruba.com/|title=Aruba: Best Island Vacation and Getaway Destination|website=www.aruba.com|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> is a 19-mile long island in the [[Caribbean]] that hosts many sports events to fuel their economy.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nAn increase in tourism revenue led to investment in athletic activities, notably recreational sports such as [[basketball]] and [[soccer]] and more island-specific pastimes such as [[kite surfing]] and [[spearfishing]]. Aruba has a soccer team that competes internationally. Many athletes from Aruba have participated in professional leagues.\n[[File:Plaza Daniel Leo, Oranjestad, Aruba - February 2020.jpg|thumb|The Plaza Daniel Leo, located in [[Oranjestad, Aruba|Oranjestad]], is where Aruba's stadiums are located. It is named after a local politician.]]\n\n== Recreational sports ==\nDue to an increase in tourism revenue, Aruba has been able to invest more into sports programs and events.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.topendsports.com/world/countries/aruba.htm|title=Sport in Aruba|website=www.topendsports.com|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> Aruba has a recreational basketball team and its citizens are very competitive in baseball and soccer.<ref name=\":1\" />Fishing and kite surfing industries have also grown significantly in recent years.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Basketball ==\nAruba's recreational [[basketball]] program consists of 16 teams, involving more than 200 players from the ages of 12 to 18. Basketball clubs have also contributed to the development of the sports on the island. One of the main objectives of the program is for one of their athletes to win an academic scholarship to play in the [[United States]]. Aruba is also making efforts to certify one of their referees for international [[FIBA]] events.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.fiba.basketball/|title=FIBA.basketball|website=FIBA.basketball|language=en|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\n== Baseball ==\n[[Baseball]], which originated in the 1930s, is one of the most popular sports on the island. Many Arubans have developed a passion for the sport, and a number subsequently went to the United States to play professionally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bio/Aruba_born.shtml|title=Players by birthplace: Aruba Baseball Stats and Info|website=Baseball-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>  The first [[Major League Baseball]] player from Aruba was [[Gene Kingsale|Eugene Humphrey Kingsale]] who played for a number of professional baseball teams from 1996-2003. \n\nBaseball's popularity can also be seen in the Aruba Little League, which originated in 1958 and has grown in popularity since then.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://arubalittleleague.org/|title=Aruba Little League|website=Aruba Little League|language=en|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> The [[San Nicolaas]] little league team won the 2010 Senior League World Series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100718151143/http://www.littleleague.org/series/2010divisions/slbb/series.htm|title=Little League Baseball|date=2010-07-18|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n== Kite Boarding ==\nThe conditions in Aruba are perfectly suited for [[Kite boarding]] year-round. The island has a favourable wind speeds, averaging around 18.5 miles per hour daily.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weatherspark.com/y/26697/Average-Weather-in-Oranjestad-Aruba-Year-Round|title=Average Weather in Oranjestad, Aruba, Year Round - Weather Spark|website=weatherspark.com|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> As the warm air is less dense than other locations, surfers can use smaller kites than would be needed in other locations. Aruba hosts many global kiteboarding tournaments, and the kiteboarding industry is one of the largest sources of income for the island.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kiteworldmag.com/|title=Kiteworld Magazine {{!}} The original international kitesurfing magazine|website=Kiteworld Magazine {{!}} The original international kitesurfing magazine|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\n== Diving ==\n{{Advert section|date=April 2020}}\nAruba has many diving locations spread across the island. The island offers various diving spots. The Island has several aeroplane wreckages.<ref name=\":0\" /> The wreck of the [[SS Antilla (1939)]] is one of the largest dive-able wrecks in the Caribbean.\n\n== National Soccer Team ==\nThe men\u2019s [[Aruba national football team]] was founded in 1932 and participated in their first international match on April 6th, 1924. They have had very little success in their international career. The team\u2019s most recent FIFA rank is 203, which is their lowest rank in history, while their highest FIFA rank was 50 in 1924. Their home stadium is the Guillermo Prospero [[Trinidad Stadium]], a multi-purpose stadium located in [[Oranjestad, Aruba|Oranjestad]], Aruba. The stadium was originally named after the former Dutch queen [[Wilhelmina of the Netherlands|Wilhelmina]], but was changed to Guillermo Prospero Trinidad Stadium in 1994.\n\nThe women\u2019s Aruban national team\u2019s current head coach is Mildred Wever. Unlike the men\u2019s team, they have not qualified for a [[FIFA Women's World Cup|World Cup]],sadly. Their current FIFA ranking is 153, their lowest FIFA ranking is 158, and their highest FIFA ranking is 92. Both teams are a part of an association named Arubaanse Voetbal Bond and both of the teams are a member of the [[CONCACAF]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Olympics ==\nPrior to 1986, athletes from Aruba competed in the Olympics representing the [[Netherlands]], but as of 1986 Aruba now fields their own athletes. Aruba has competed in 9 Summer [[Olympic Games]], but has yet to win any medals. A notable Olympian, [[Miguel Janssen]], currently holds the country\u2019s record in most long-distance running events. He participated for [[Aruba at the 1996 Summer Olympics|Aruba in the 1996 summer games]], as well as in 6 different world championships for Aruba.  Aruba has yet to participate in any [[Winter Olympic Games|winter games]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.topendsports.com/events/summer/countries/aruba.htm|title=Aruba at the Olympic Games|website=www.topendsports.com|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n== Local Sports Facilities ==\nThe Don Elias Mansur Ballpark is a multi-use stadium and is used mainly for baseball games. The Guillermo Prospero Trinidad Stadium is another multi-use stadium and is used by the national soccer teams as well as by track and field teams. The Tierra Del Sol Resort, Spa and Country Club is the only 18 hole golf course in Aruba.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Professional Athletes ==\n\n* [[Calvin Maduro]]\n* [[Gene Kingsale]]\n* [[Radhames Dykhoff]]\n* [[Sidney Ponson]]\n* [[Xander Bogaerts]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Sport in Aruba]]\n", "text_old": "{{copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n[[Aruba]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aruba.com/|title=Aruba: Best Island Vacation and Getaway Destination|website=www.aruba.com|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> is a 19-mile long island in the [[Caribbean]] that hosts many sports events to fuel their economy.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nAn increase in tourism revenue led to investment in athletic activities, notably recreational sports such as [[basketball]] and [[soccer]] and more island-specific pastimes such as [[kite surfing]] and [[spearfishing]]. Aruba has a soccer team that competes internationally. Many athletes from Aruba have participated in professional leagues.\n[[File:Plaza Daniel Leo, Oranjestad, Aruba - February 2020.jpg|thumb|The Plaza Daniel Leo, located in [[Oranjestad, Aruba|Oranjestad]], is where Aruba's stadiums are located. It is named after a local politician.]]\n\n== Recreational sports ==\nDue to an increase in tourism revenue, Aruba has been able to invest more into sports programs and events.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.topendsports.com/world/countries/aruba.htm|title=Sport in Aruba|website=www.topendsports.com|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> Aruba has a recreational basketball team and its citizens are very competitive in baseball and soccer.<ref name=\":1\" />Fishing and kite surfing industries have also grown significantly in recent years.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Basketball ==\nAruba's recreational [[basketball]] program consists of 16 teams, involving more than 200 players from the ages of 12 to 18. Basketball clubs have also contributed to the development of the sports on the island. One of the main objectives of the program is for one of their athletes to win an academic scholarship to play in the [[United States]]. Aruba is also making efforts to certify one of their referees for international [[FIBA]] events.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.fiba.basketball/|title=FIBA.basketball|website=FIBA.basketball|language=en|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\n== Baseball ==\n[[Baseball]], which originated in the 1930s, is one of the most popular sports on the island. Many Arubans have developed a passion for the sport, and a number subsequently went to the United States to play professionally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bio/Aruba_born.shtml|title=Players by birthplace: Aruba Baseball Stats and Info|website=Baseball-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>  The first [[Major League Baseball]] player from Aruba was [[Gene Kingsale|Eugene Humphrey Kingsale]] who played for a number of professional baseball teams from 1996-2003. \n\nBaseball's popularity can also be seen in the Aruba Little League, which originated in 1958 and has grown in popularity since then.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://arubalittleleague.org/|title=Aruba Little League|website=Aruba Little League|language=en|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> The [[San Nicolaas]] little league team won the 2010 Senior League World Series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100718151143/http://www.littleleague.org/series/2010divisions/slbb/series.htm|title=Little League Baseball|date=2010-07-18|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n== Kite Boarding ==\nThe conditions in Aruba are perfectly suited for [[Kite boarding]] year-round. The island has a favourable wind speeds, averaging around 18.5 miles per hour daily.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://weatherspark.com/y/26697/Average-Weather-in-Oranjestad-Aruba-Year-Round|title=Average Weather in Oranjestad, Aruba, Year Round - Weather Spark|website=weatherspark.com|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> As the warm air is less dense than other locations, surfers can use smaller kites than would be needed in other locations. Aruba hosts many global kiteboarding tournaments, and the kiteboarding industry is one of the largest sources of income for the island.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kiteworldmag.com/|title=Kiteworld Magazine {{!}} The original international kitesurfing magazine|website=Kiteworld Magazine {{!}} The original international kitesurfing magazine|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\n== Diving ==\n{{Advert section|date=April 2020}}\nAruba has many diving locations spread across the island. The island offers various diving spots including Pedernales, Jane Sea Wreck, Serito Pinnacle. The Island has several aeroplane wreckages.<ref name=\":0\" /> The wreck of the [[SS Antilla (1939)]] is one of the largest dive-able wrecks in the Caribbean.\n\n== National Soccer Team ==\nThe men\u2019s [[Aruba national football team]] was founded in 1932 and participated in their first international match on April 6th, 1924. They have had very little success in their international career. The team\u2019s most recent FIFA rank is 203, which is their lowest rank in history, while their highest FIFA rank was 50 in 1924. Their home stadium is the Guillermo Prospero [[Trinidad Stadium]], a multi-purpose stadium located in [[Oranjestad, Aruba|Oranjestad]], Aruba. The stadium was originally named after the former Dutch queen [[Wilhelmina of the Netherlands|Wilhelmina]], but was changed to Guillermo Prospero Trinidad Stadium in 1994.\n\nThe women\u2019s Aruban national team\u2019s current head coach is Mildred Wever. Unlike the men\u2019s team, they have not qualified for a [[FIFA Women's World Cup|World Cup]],sadly. Their current FIFA ranking is 153, their lowest FIFA ranking is 158, and their highest FIFA ranking is 92. Both teams are a part of an association named Arubaanse Voetbal Bond and both of the teams are a member of the [[CONCACAF]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Olympics ==\nPrior to 1986, athletes from Aruba competed in the Olympics representing the [[Netherlands]], but as of 1986 Aruba now fields their own athletes. Aruba has competed in 9 Summer [[Olympic Games]], but has yet to win any medals. A notable Olympian, [[Miguel Janssen]], currently holds the country\u2019s record in most long-distance running events. He participated for [[Aruba at the 1996 Summer Olympics|Aruba in the 1996 summer games]], as well as in 6 different world championships for Aruba.  Aruba has yet to participate in any [[Winter Olympic Games|winter games]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.topendsports.com/events/summer/countries/aruba.htm|title=Aruba at the Olympic Games|website=www.topendsports.com|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n== Local Sports Facilities ==\nThe Don Elias Mansur Ballpark is a multi-use stadium and is used mainly for baseball games. The Guillermo Prospero Trinidad Stadium is another multi-use stadium and is used by the national soccer teams as well as by track and field teams. The Tierra Del Sol Resort, Spa and Country Club is the only 18 hole golf course in Aruba.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Professional Athletes ==\n\n* [[Calvin Maduro]]\n* [[Gene Kingsale]]\n* [[Radhames Dykhoff]]\n* [[Sidney Ponson]]\n* [[Xander Bogaerts]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Sport in Aruba]]\n", "name_user": "Stmape", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDiving", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sports_in_Aruba"}
